Patch-Source: https://github.com/caronc/apprise/issues/XXXX

The autouse no_throttling_everywhere fixture is function-scoped but used the
session-scoped mocker, so the patches it applies to every plugin on every test
were never released until the whole session ended.  With 143 plugins over
~1650 tests that accumulates ~230k active patches, and because
unittest.mock.patch.stop() removes itself from a global list, the final
stopall() at session teardown becomes O(n^2) and hangs for minutes.  It
surfaces as a pytest-timeout on whichever test happens to run last
(tests/test_utils_wkd.py, alphabetically near the end).

Switch to the function-scoped mocker so each patch is undone at the end of its
test; the active-patch list then stays bounded at len(plugins).

--- a/tests/conftest.py
+++ b/tests/conftest.py
@@ -57,8 +57,8 @@


 @pytest.fixture(scope="function", autouse=True)
-def no_throttling_everywhere(session_mocker):
-    """A pytest session fixture which disables throttling on all notifiers.
+def no_throttling_everywhere(mocker):
+    """A pytest function fixture which disables throttling on all notifiers.

     It is automatically enabled.
     """
@@ -67,8 +67,15 @@
     C_MGR.unload_modules()
     A_MGR.unload_modules()

+    # Use the function-scoped ``mocker`` (not ``session_mocker``) so each
+    # patch is undone at the end of the test.  This fixture re-patches every
+    # plugin on every test; with ``session_mocker`` the patches were never
+    # released until the session ended, accumulating len(plugins) * len(tests)
+    # (~230k) active patches.  unittest.mock.patch.stop() removes from a global
+    # list, so the final stopall() became O(n^2) and the session teardown
+    # hung for minutes -- surfacing as a "timeout" on whichever test ran last.
     for plugin in N_MGR.plugins():
-        session_mocker.patch.object(plugin, "request_rate_per_sec", 0)
+        mocker.patch.object(plugin, "request_rate_per_sec", 0)


 @pytest.fixture(scope="function", autouse=True)
